Requirement

pathwaygene set score After functionally annotating single-cell subpopulations, how can I calculate the gene set score for a specific pathway in each subpopulation?

https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.118.038362 From https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.118.038362

Figure 5. Pathway analysis of endothelial cell (EC) subpopulations. B, Functional gene sets identified from Reactome pathway enrichment and subpopulation markers differentiate the 2 major EC populations EC 1 and EC 2.

Application Scenario

matrixGSVApathwaypathway Single-cell data: From matrix to grouping, calculate pathway expression using GSVA, then compare pathway differences between groups and plot.

seurat: Several points to note when using Seurat to analyze single-cell data:

1.

1. Data filtering

  1. <200 > 7500

  2. Filter out cells with <200 or >7500 expressed genes. The upper and lower limits of the filter are controlled by yourself and there is no fixed value. Filtering out genes with high expression is to reduce the proportion of multiple cells

  3. <3 00

  4. Filter out genes that are expressed in <3 cells. Because many genes have an expression value of 0, this method can filter out many genes with all zero expressions

  6. The proportion of mitochondrial genes, to a certain extent, represents the integrity of the cells when the library was built. If the mitochondrial gene ratio is too high, its very likely that the cells are damaged and incomplete during the oil-water mixture.

MT genes% < 20% MT genes% < 20% or so. This should be controlled based on your data. Even if the filtering here is not strict, it doesnt matter; cells with a high mitochondrial gene ratio will be clustered together during subsequent clustering.

These cells can simply be excluded from subsequent analysis. Mitochondrial gene ratios are generally very low in peripheral blood data.

2

2 Clustering and Dimensionality Reduction Visualization

PCAPCresolution There are two parameters that are difficult to control: the number of PCs in the PCA results and the resolution.

  • PCElbowPlot()PC
  • resolutionclusterresolutioncluster
  • For the number of PCs, select the number of PCs near the inflection point using the ElbowPlot (inflection point plot). This parameter affects the clustering results and subsequent dimensionality reduction graphs.
  • Resolution: This parameter is relatively unimportant and only affects the number of clusters generated. A high resolution will result in a large number of clusters, which can be useful in subsequent analysis.

marker genescluster Define cell types based on marker genes and other factors, and then manually merge clusters of the same cell type.

5000 - 10000 resolution = 1 2 Generally, for cells between 5,000 and 10,000, selecting resolution = 1 is sufficient. For larger cell numbers, you can choose 2. Adjust this setting based on the desired resolution; it does not affect the overall result.

#  STEP 1 pbmc / Load PBMC obtained in Step 1
pbmc <- readRDS("PBMC_pc10_res0.6.rds")

# gmt / Import gmt file
genesets <- getGmt("h.all.v7.0.symbols.gmt")

### 1.  / Find cell groups of interest and compare them
subcluster <- c(6, 8)
sub <- subset(pbmc, idents = subcluster)
df.data <- GetAssayData(object = sub, slot = "data")

# group / Save cell group information
df.group <- data.frame(
  umi = names(Idents(sub)), 
  cluster = as.character(sub@meta.data$RNA_snn_res.0.6), 
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE
)

### 2. gsva -  / Perform GSVA - fix parameter passing issues
#  / Ensure correct data format
expr_data <- as.matrix(df.data)

# genesetsgsva / Convert genesets to the format required by gsva
# GSEABase::getGmt()GeneSetCollection
geneset_list <- lapply(genesets, function(gs) {
  GSEABase::geneIds(gs)
})
names(geneset_list) <- names(genesets)

# gsva / Call gsva with correct parameter format
param <- gsvaParam(
  exprData = expr_data,
  geneSets = geneset_list,
  kcdf = "Gaussian"
)

gsvascore <- gsva(
  param,
  verbose = TRUE
)

  # ComplexHeatmap

### 4.  / Differential analysis
cluster.group <- as.numeric(df.group$cluster)
group2 <- 6
cluster.group[cluster.group != group2] <- 0
cluster.group[cluster.group == group2] <- 1

design <- model.matrix(~ cluster.group)
colnames(design) <- c("Intercept", "Group2vs1")

# limma / Perform differential analysis using limma
if (!require(limma)) {
  install.packages("limma")
  library(limma)
}

fit <- lmFit(gsvascore, design)
fit <- eBayes(fit)

#  / Get significant pathways
sigPathways <- topTable(
  fit, 
  coef = "Group2vs1", 
  number = Inf, 
  p.value = 0.05, 
  adjust.method = "BH"
)

#  / Add grouping information
if (nrow(sigPathways) > 0) {
  sigPathways$celltype <- rep(group2, nrow(sigPathways))
  
  #  / Save results
  write.csv(
    sigPathways, 
    file = "PBMC_DE_genesets_hallmarker_cluster6_vs_8.csv",
    row.names = TRUE
  )
  
  print(paste("Found / ", nrow(sigPathways), "significant pathways / "))
  print(head(sigPathways))
} else {
  print("No significant pathways found with p.value < 0.05 / p<0.05")
}

STEP 3: Based on the obtained grouping information, select the desired pathways and plot them.

sigPathwaysgene set Select a gene set from sigPathways to demonstrate how to plot an example plot. You can also create a loop to plot multiple plots.

# pathway
# Select the first pathway to plot
count <- gsvascore[rownames(sigPathways)[1], , drop = FALSE]
count <- as.data.frame(t(count))
colnames(count) <- "geneset"
count$cluster <- as.character(Idents(sub))
# 
# Use the name of the pathway as the graph title
title.name = rownames(sigPathways)[1]

# P
# cluster6cluster10gsva score 
# Add P value
# Get the maximum gsva score in cluster6 and cluster10
count.geneset.group1 <- count$geneset[count$cluster == subcluster[1]]
count.geneset.group2 <- count$geneset[count$cluster == subcluster[2]]

# P
# Determine the position to add the P value
ysegment1 <- max(count.geneset.group1)
ysegment2 <- max(count.geneset.group2)
ysegment.max <- max(ysegment1, ysegment2)

# P
# Add stars based on P value
pval <- sigPathways$P.Value[1]

if (pval < 0.001) {
  pval.label = "***"
} else if (pval < 0.005) {
  pval.label = "**"
} else if (pval < 0.05) {
  pval.label = "*"
} else if (pval >= 0.05) {
  pval.label = "non.sig"
}

# 
# Custom color
blue <- "#619CD6"
green <- "#89C32E"
p <- ggplot(count, aes(x = cluster, y = geneset, fill = cluster)) +
  geom_violin() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(blue, green)) + #  # Fill with custom color
  theme_classic() +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank(), 
        plot.margin = margin(0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, "cm"), 
        axis.title.x = element_text(color = "black", size = 20), 
        axis.title.y = element_blank(), 
        axis.text = element_text(color = "black", size = 16), 
        axis.line = element_line(colour = "black", size = 0.6), 
        plot.title = element_text(size = 20, hjust = 0.5)) + 
  #  # Add graph title
  ggtitle(title.name) +
  guides(fill = F)

  #  # One horizontal line and two vertical lines in the graph
  annotate("segment", x = 1, xend = 2, y = ysegment.max + 0.02, yend = ysegment.max + 0.02) + 
  annotate("segment", x = 1, xend = 1, y = ysegment1 + 0.01, yend = ysegment.max + 0.02) +
